Interpretation
Structural Equation Modeling (SEM) using path analysis was applied to study how different apple attributes influence apple quality. The dataset contained 4000 observations and the model was estimated using Maximum Likelihood (ML) after removing the ID column and converting Quality into numeric form (1 = good, 0 = bad).

The model examines how Size and Crunchiness affect taste attributes (Sweetness, Juiciness, Acidity) and how these attributes influence the final quality of apples.

Model Fit
The model shows a moderately acceptable fit.

Chi-square = 367.64 (df = 6, p < 0.001) indicating some difference between model and observed data.

CFI = 0.850, indicating moderate fit.

TLI = 0.626, below the ideal threshold but improved from earlier models.

RMSEA = 0.123, slightly higher than the recommended range (0.05–0.08).

SRMR = 0.070, which is within the acceptable limit (<0.08).

Overall, the model reasonably explains the relationships among apple attributes.

Structural Relationships
Effects on Taste Attributes

Size → Sweetness = −0.325: Larger apples tend to be less sweet.

Size → Juiciness = 0.026: Size has a very small positive effect on juiciness.

Crunchiness → Juiciness = −0.264: Crunchier apples tend to be less juicy.

Size → Acidity = 0.092: Larger apples slightly increase acidity.

Direct Effects on Apple Quality

Size → Quality = 0.378: Strongest positive effect on quality.

Sweetness → Quality = 0.360: Sweeter apples increase quality.

Juiciness → Quality = 0.268: Juiciness positively influences quality.

Acidity → Quality = −0.149: Higher acidity reduces quality.

Covariance
There is a positive covariance between Size and Crunchiness (0.170), meaning larger apples tend to be slightly crunchier.

Conclusion

The analysis shows that Size, Sweetness, and Juiciness are the most important factors influencing apple quality, while high acidity negatively affects quality. Although larger apples generally increase perceived quality, they may reduce sweetness and increase acidity. Overall, the model provides a reasonable explanation of apple quality, though additional factors such as color, variety, or aroma could further improve the model.


